{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505771"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:35:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:35:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2477"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2477"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.01,0.59,0.12,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103112"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2477"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85573"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1758"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2176"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15335"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28843"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35725"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43163"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103112"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-year history of persistent cough productive of copious, foul-smelling yellow sputum. He also reports progressive breathlessness. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has never smoked. He works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 84/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Bilateral crackles and wheezes are heard on chest auscultation. A chest X-ray shows increased pulmonary markings and linear atelectasis in both lung fields.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchoscopy with biopsy","Full blood count","High-resolution CT scan of the chest","Pulmonary function tests","Sputum gram staining and culture"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of bronchiectasis: chronic productive cough with copious, foul-smelling sputum. The non-specific chest X-ray findings require further investigation for definitive diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBronchiectasis is most often the result of a primary chronic lung infections that were either not treated or inadequately treated leading to the bronchial wall damage and dilatation of bronchioles. However it is also associated with gastro-oesophageal reflux, alpha-1-atitrypsin deficiency, Crohn\u0027s disease, rheumatoid arthritis, cystic fibrosis and environmental exposures. These insults significantly impair the mucus clearance leading to colonisation of pathogenic organisms and thus resulting in purulent expectorations seen in this disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-resolution CT scan of the chest\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard investigation for diagnosing bronchiectasis. It demonstrates characteristic features including bronchial dilatation, bronchial wall thickening (signet ring sign), and lack of bronchial tapering.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy with biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely required for diagnosing bronchiectasis. It may be indicated if there is concern about an underlying structural lesion or to obtain samples in cases of resistant infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFull blood count\u003C/strong\u003E may show neutrophilia during exacerbations but is non-specific and cannot confirm the diagnosis of bronchiectasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary function tests\u003C/strong\u003E typically show an obstructive pattern in bronchiectasis but cannot differentiate it from other obstructive lung diseases such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum gram staining and culture\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for identifying pathogens during exacerbations and guiding antimicrobial therapy but does not confirm the underlying diagnosis of bronchiectasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming bronchiectasis on CT, further investigations are often required to identify any underlying cause such as immunodeficiency, alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency, or primary ciliary dyskinesia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High-resolution CT chest is the gold standard for diagnosing bronchiectasis, showing bronchial dilation and wall thickening.","Bronchiectasis typically presents with chronic productive cough with copious, foul-smelling sputum.","Chest X-ray findings are often non-specific in bronchiectasis and cannot reliably confirm the diagnosis."],"references":["Smith MP. Diagnosis and management of bronchiectasis. CMAJ. 2017 Jun 19;189(24):E828-E835. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28630359/","Gaillard F, Silverstone L, Di Muzio B, et al. Bronchiectasis. Radiopaedia.org. https://radiopaedia.org/articles/bronchiectasis. Accessed May 19, 2025."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85573"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2477"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85573"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-19T20:38:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-19T20:39:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2477"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103112"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"typ